  "Several genuine Lake Superior agates, confirmed by an experienced local collector, photographed dry (not wet, no special lighting). Note how subtle they look: muted rust/tan/cream coloring rather than vivid color, a pitted or slightly frosted rind texture on several of them, and only faint hints of banding or translucency at some edges. This is a realistic example of what a genuine agate looks like in an ordinary dry photo -- do not expect the vivid wet look described elsewhere in these instructions when judging a dry rock.";

